1 Background

As a statistical consultant working for a real estate investment firm, your task is to develop a model to predict the selling price of a given home in Ames, Iowa. Your employer hopes to use this information to help assess whether the asking price of a house is higher or lower than the true value of the house. If the home is undervalued, it may be a good investment for the firm.

2 Training Data and relevant packages

In order to better assess the quality of the model you will produce, the data have been randomly divided into three separate pieces: a training data set, a testing data set, and a validation data set. For now we will load the training data set, the others will be loaded and used later.

load("ames_train.Rdata")

Use the code block below to load any necessary packages

library(BAS)
library(MASS)
library(dplyr)
library(GGally)
library(statsr)
library(ggplot2)
# disable scientific notation
options(scipen=999)

2.1 Part 1 - Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

When you first get your data, its very tempting to immediately begin fitting models and assessing how they perform. However, before you begin modeling, its absolutely essential to explore the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set.

Do a detailed EDA of the ames_train data set, to learn about the structure of the data and the relationships between the variables in the data set (refer to Introduction to Probability and Data, Week 2, for a reminder about EDA if needed). Your EDA should involve creating and reviewing many plots/graphs and considering the patterns and relationships you see.

After you have explored completely, submit the three graphs/plots that you found most informative during your EDA process, and briefly explain what you learned from each (why you found each informative).

Heres the plot of the distribution of prices:

ggplot(data = ames_train, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram(bins=30)

The distribution is right skewed, which makes sense for house prices. Most of the house prices cost less then $400000 with only a few (25) houses above that price.

Next here are the neighborhoods and how they relate to house prices:

ames_train_neighborhood <- ames_train %>% group_by(Neighborhood) %>% summarise(price_median = median(price))
ggplot(ames_train_neighborhood, aes(Neighborhood, price_median)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + coord_flip()

StoneBr and NridgHt are two of the most expensive neighborhoods and the cheapest neighborhood is MeadowV.

Finally heres the correlation plot between price and area:

ggpairs(ames_train[, c('price', 'area')])

The plot above indicates that there is a somewhat of a linear relationship between area and price (correlation coefficient is high compared to other variables; scatter plot is fairly linear). This makes sense because the bigger the house the more its going to cost.

2.2 Part 2 - Development and assessment of an initial model, following a semi-guided process of analysis

2.2.1 Section 2.1 An Initial Model

In building a model, it is often useful to start by creating a simple, intuitive initial model based on the results of the exploratory data analysis. (Note: The goal at this stage is not to identify the best possible model but rather to choose a reasonable and understandable starting point. Later you will expand and revise this model to create your final model.

Based on your EDA, select at most 10 predictor variables from ames_train and create a linear model for price (or a transformed version of price) using those variables. Provide the R code and the summary output table for your model, a brief justification for the variables you have chosen, and a brief discussion of the model results in context (focused on the variables that appear to be important predictors and how they relate to sales price).

Before doing any modeling Ill filter out sales conditions that are not normal (reasoning behind this is that other types of sales conditions can have unusually low/high prices and that can throw the model performance off):

ames_train <- ames_train %>% filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")

Below I build the initial model and print out the summary output table:

init_model <- lm(log(price) ~ log(area) + Year.Built + Bedroom.AbvGr + Total.Bsmt.SF + Central.Air + Kitchen.Qual + Garage.Area + Functional, ames_train)

After looking at the summary table, all of the features except Kitchen.Qual and Functional are statistically significant (if one level of the factor is insignificant then the entire variable is insignificant). log(area) and Central.Air have the biggest coefficients. log(area) also has the biggest t value which makes it the most important predictor. That makes sense because just based on how large the house is (meaning the area of the house) we can roughly guess the price.

2.2.3 Section 2.3 Initial Model Residuals

One way to assess the performance of a model is to examine the models residuals. In the space below, create a residual plot for your preferred model from above and use it to assess whether your model appears to fit the data well. Comment on any interesting structure in the residual plot (trend, outliers, etc.) and briefly discuss potential implications it may have for your model and inference / prediction you might produce.

ggplot(init_model, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point()

The plot above shows that residuals are mostly randomly scattered around 0 which is good but there might be one potential outlier/influential point. That point is at ~11.5 on the X axis and ~-0.8 on y axis. Usually this sort of an outlier can negatively effect model performance by influencing the slope of the regression line.

2.2.4 Section 2.4 Initial Model RMSE

You can calculate it directly based on the model output. Be specific about the units of your RMSE (depending on whether you transformed your response variable). The value you report will be more meaningful if it is in the original units (dollars).

predicted_conv_train <- exp(predict(init_model, ames_train))
sqrt(mean((ames_train$price - predicted_conv_train)^2))
## [1] 25248.45

I calculated the RMSE in the code above and got a result of 25248.45. I converted the scale back to the original units which means RMSE is in dollars. One way to interpret RMSE is as a measure of how close the predicted values are to the actual/observed data points (on average). The lower the RMSE the better. Perfect model (that very likely doesnt exist and is overfitting) would have an RMSE of 0. Once I calculate RMSE on the test set Ill have a better idea of how the model performs in the real world.

2.2.5 Section 2.5 Overfitting

The process of building a model generally involves starting with an initial model (as you have done above), identifying its shortcomings, and adapting the model accordingly. This process may be repeated several times until the model fits the data reasonably well. However, the model may do well on training data but perform poorly out-of-sample (meaning, on a dataset other than the original training data) because the model is overly-tuned to specifically fit the training data. This is called overfitting. To determine whether overfitting is occurring on a model, compare the performance of a model on both in-sample and out-of-sample data sets. To look at performance of your initial model on out-of-sample data, you will use the data set ames_test.

load("ames_test.Rdata")

Use your model from above to generate predictions for the housing prices in the test data set. Are the predictions significantly more accurate (compared to the actual sales prices) for the training data than the test data? Why or why not? Briefly explain how you determined that (what steps or processes did you use)?

# remove non normal sales conditions
ames_test <- ames_test %>% filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")
# get predictions
preds_test <- predict(init_model, ames_test)

# calculate RMSE
conv_prices <- exp(preds_test)
sqrt(mean((ames_test$price - conv_prices)^2))
## [1] 26402.39

RMSE on the test set is 26402.39, which is a bit higher then the RMSE on the training dataset. The model is slightly overfitting on the training dataset, but the difference between the RMSEs is not large, thus this shouldnt cause a lot of problems.

Note to the learner: If in real-life practice this out-of-sample analysis shows evidence that the training data fits your model a lot better than the test data, it is probably a good idea to go back and revise the model (usually by simplifying the model) to reduce this overfitting. For simplicity, we do not ask you to do this on the assignment, however.

2.3.2 Section 3.2 Transformation

Did you decide to transform any variables? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

I ended up log transforming the dependent variable price because the distribution of the price was right skewed. I also ended up log transforming area because the relationship between price and area was more linear if the transformation was performed.

2.3.3 Section 3.3 Variable Interaction

Did you decide to include any variable interactions? Why or why not? Explain in a few sentences.

I did not include any variable interactions because the model seems to perform well without them.

2.3.4 Section 3.4 Variable Selection

What method did you use to select the variables you included? Why did you select the method you used? Explain in a few sentences.

For my model selection technique I used backwards elimination with AIC as a criterion. Its a standard method for model selection that seems to work well for this problem/dataset.

2.3.5 Section 3.5 Model Testing

How did testing the model on out-of-sample data affect whether or how you changed your model? Explain in a few sentences.

Testing my final model on out-of-sample data did not change my model. RMSE of the final model on the out-of-sample data was a bit higher then the RMSE on the training dataset, but the difference was relatively small so I was comfortable with not changing the model itself.

2.4 Part 4 Final Model Assessment

2.4.1 Section 4.1 Final Model Residual

For your final model, create and briefly interpret an informative plot of the residuals.

ggplot(final_model, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point()

Plot above looks good. Residuals seem to be randomly scattered around 0 and there are no obvious patterns in the plot.

2.4.2 Section 4.2 Final Model RMSE

For your final model, calculate and briefly comment on the RMSE.

RMSE of the final model on the training dataset: 21297.28

RMSE of the final model on the test/out-of-sample dataset: 23508.09

RMSE of the final model on both training and out-of-sample datasets was lower then the baseline model which is great and means that the final model is better then the baseline model (based on the RMSE). The difference between training and out-of-sample RMSEs of the final model is not big so Im not concerned about overfitting.

2.4.3 Section 4.3 Final Model Evaluation

What are some strengths and weaknesses of your model?

Strengths:

  • RMSE on both training & test set is better than the baseline
  • No immediate evidence of overfitting

Weaknesses:

  • Its a linear model. There are very likely non linear relationships Im not capturing, that if captured by a non linear model (ie tree based models) would help with predicting house prices.

2.4.4 Section 4.4 Final Model Validation

Testing your final model on a separate, validation data set is a great way to determine how your model will perform in real-life practice.

You will use the ames_validation dataset to do some additional assessment of your final model. Discuss your findings, be sure to mention:

  • What is the RMSE of your final model when applied to the validation data?
  • How does this value compare to that of the training data and/or testing data?
  • What percentage of the 95% predictive confidence (or credible) intervals contain the true price of the house in the validation data set?
  • From this result, does your final model properly reflect uncertainty?
load("ames_validation.Rdata")
# remove non normal sales conditions
ames_validation <- ames_validation %>% filter(Sale.Condition == "Normal")

# remove "A" level from MS Zoning since that level does not exist in the train or test dataset
ames_validation <- droplevels(ames_validation[!ames_validation$MS.Zoning == "A (agr)", ])

# remove any values with "Floor" values for "Heating" since we didn't have that in the training and test sets
floor_factor <- which(ames_validation$Heating == "Floor")
ames_validation <- ames_validation[-floor_factor,]
# RMSE Validation - Final Model
preds_validation_final <- predict(final_model, ames_validation)
conv_prices_validation_final <- exp(preds_validation_final)
sqrt(mean((ames_validation$price - conv_prices_validation_final)^2, na.rm=TRUE))
## [1] 22576.89

RMSE is 22576.89 which is higher then the RMSE on the training set, but lower then the RMSE on the test set. Im pretty happy with that RMSE given that its on the validation set.

preds_interval <- predict(final_model, ames_validation, interval = "prediction")
preds_interval <- exp(preds_interval)
coverage_validation <- mean(ames_validation$price > preds_interval[,"lwr"] & ames_validation$price < preds_interval[,"upr"], na.rm = TRUE)
coverage_validation
## [1] 0.9263158

93% of true values are within the 95% predictive confidence interval. Ideally that number would be 95% but 93% is close enough that I can say that model reflects uncertainty pretty well.

2.5 Part 5 Conclusion

Provide a brief summary of your results, and a brief discussion of what you have learned about the data and your model.

final_model is a decent model but it could be a lot better. One of the main limitations is the fact that I only worked with houses that got sold under a Normal Sale.Condition. I did this to avoid unusually high or unusually low prices that occur in other Sale.Conditions but those still happen in the real world. One way to overcome this limitation is to gather more data on those houses and build a model specifically for those Sale.Conditions or maybe an ensemble of models. Another major limitation is that I am using linear models. Non linear models that capture non linear relationships would likely work better.
